 unique interpretations and confrontations with the modern period and its relationship to those who presumably fall outside its boundaries of self-consciousness. Expanding the conversation, Mohaghegh contrasts the impressions of the Middle Eastern figures considered with those of the most incisive Western thinkers of modernity, such as Nietzsche, Heidegger, and Baudrillard, to offer an original global vision that crosses the East-West divide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPersian literaturexWestern influences. 0aPostmodernism (Literature). 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845612640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438456126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438456126/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles